                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Vernon Mauery",
                        "email": "vernon.mauery@linux.intel.com",
                        "username": "vmauery"
                    },
                    "message": "I really hesitate defining a new class.\n\nHere is the minimum change I have come up with that works:\n\n\ntemplate <typename T>\nclass SecureAllocator : public std::allocator<T>\n{\n};\ntemplate <typename T>\nclass SecureAllocator : public std::allocator<T>\n{\n  public:\n    template <typename U>\n    struct rebind\n    {\n        typedef SecureAllocator<U> other;\n    };\n\n    void deallocate(T* p, size_t n)\n    {\n        OPENSSL_cleanse(p, n);\n        return std::allocator<T>::deallocate(p, n);\n    }\n};\n\nusing SecureString =\n    std::basic_string<char, std::char_traits<char>, SecureAllocator<char>>;\n\n// Zero the string on destruction (alloc'd or internal)\ntemplate <>\nSecureString::~SecureString()\n{\n    OPENSSL_cleanse(&((*this)[0]), this->size());\n}\n\n\nI tested this using a class to capture the string pointer and len prior to changes (+, =, std::move) and then inspected the memory after."
